<section id="section-2a">
<title> Planar components of a vector </title>
<para id="element-73a">
The planar components of a vector lies in the plane of vector. Since there are two perpendicular axes involved with a plane, a vector is resolved in two components which lie in the same plane as that of vector. Clearly, a vector is composed of components in only two directions :
</para>
<para id="element-74b">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
  <m:mtr>
  <m:mtd>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> a </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> cos </m:mi>
  <m:mi> α </m:mi>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> i </m:mi>
  <m:mo> + </m:mo>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> cos </m:mi>
  <m:mi> β </m:mi>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> j </m:mi>
  </m:mtd>
  </m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-75a">
From the figure depicting a planar coordinate, it is clear that angle “β” is compliment of angle “α”. If α = θ, then 
</para>
<para id="element-76a">
<figure id="fig-76a">
<title> Planar vector </title>
<media id="id1163789353145" alt=""><image src="../../media/va11.gif" mime-type="image/gif"/></media>
<caption> The direction of a planar vector with respect to rectangular axes can be described by a single angle.</caption>
</figure>

</para>
<para id="element-77a">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
  <m:mtr>
  <m:mtd>
  <m:mi> α </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
  <m:mspace width="4pt"/>
  <m:mi> and </m:mi>
  <m:mspace width="4pt"/>
  <m:mi> β </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
  <m:mn> 90 </m:mn>
  <m:mo> ° </m:mo>
  <m:mo> - </m:mo>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
  </m:mtd>
  </m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-78">
Putting in the expression for the vector,
</para>
<para id="element-79">
<equation id="equation-79">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
  <m:mtr>
  <m:mtd>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> a </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
  <m:msub>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> x </m:mi>
  </m:msub>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> i </m:mi>
  <m:mo> + </m:mo>
  <m:msub>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> y </m:mi>
  </m:msub>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> j </m:mi>
  </m:mtd>
  </m:mtr>
  <m:mtr>
  <m:mtd>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> a </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> cos </m:mi>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> i </m:mi>
  <m:mo> + </m:mo>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> cos </m:mi>
  <m:mo> ( </m:mo>
  <m:mn> 90 </m:mn>
  <m:mo> ° </m:mo>
  <m:mo> - </m:mo>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
  <m:mo> ) </m:mo>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> j </m:mi>
  </m:mtd>
  </m:mtr>
  <m:mtr>
  <m:mtd>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> a </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> cos </m:mi>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> i </m:mi>
  <m:mo> + </m:mo>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> sin </m:mi>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
  <m:mi mathvariant="bold"> j </m:mi>
  </m:mtd>
  </m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</equation>
</para>
<para id="element-80">
From graphical representation, the tangent of the angle that vector makes with x-axis is :
</para>
<para id="element-81">
<equation id="equation-81">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
  <m:mtr>
  <m:mtd>
  <m:mi> tan </m:mi>
  <m:mi> α </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
  <m:mi> tan </m:mi>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> sin </m:mi>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
  <m:mi> a </m:mi>
  <m:mi> cos </m:mi>
  <m:mi> θ </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
  <m:mo> = </m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
